I call the following "The Japanese Number Haiku."
It is not a "translation"; it is merely the japanese hiraana rendering of my preferred words for the numbers one to ten
- but, alas, I wonder if it is merely a coincidence that the number of characters strung together in the traditional japanese way fulfill the classical haiku length of 17 syllables:

Ichinisan
Shikorokunanaha
Chikuuyuu

Note: the number eight ("hachi") spills over across lines two and three. This is not proper, yet we will accept it because of the strange coincidence noted above.
